{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617020"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:09:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:09:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16452"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16452"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.59,0.07,0.07,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9143"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65955"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9143"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16452"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51404"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3996"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21716"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21721"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65955"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common seizure type in adults with epilepsy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Focal seizures","Generalised tonic-clonic seizures","Absence seizures","Myoclonic seizures","Atonic seizures"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFocal seizures\u003C/strong\u003E (previously called partial seizures) are the most common type of seizure in adults with epilepsy, accounting for approximately 60% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGeneralised tonic-clonic seizures\u003C/strong\u003E may occur either as primary generalised seizures or as focal seizures that evolve to bilateral tonic-clonic seizures (previously called secondary generalised seizures). While dramatic in presentation, primary generalised tonic-clonic seizures are less common than focal seizures in adults.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbsence seizures\u003C/strong\u003E typically begin in childhood and are characterised by brief lapses in awareness without motor manifestations. They are relatively uncommon in adults.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyoclonic seizures\u003C/strong\u003E involve sudden, brief muscle jerks and are most commonly seen in specific epilepsy syndromes such as juvenile myoclonic epilepsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtonic seizures\u003C/strong\u003E involve a sudden loss of muscle tone causing falls and are relatively rare, typically occurring in the context of severe epilepsy syndromes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe terminology for seizure classification has evolved over time, moving away from terms like \u0027partial\u0027 and \u0027secondary generalised\u0027 to \u0027focal\u0027 and \u0027focal to bilateral tonic-clonic\u0027 respectively. This new terminology better reflects the underlying pathophysiology and network involvement in seizure propagation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Focal seizures (previously called partial seizures) are the most common type of seizure in adults with epilepsy.","Focal seizures may evolve to bilateral tonic-clonic seizures (previously called secondary generalised seizures).","The classification of seizures has evolved from partial/generalised to focal/generalised terminology."],"references":["Epilepsy Action Australia [Internet]. 2017. Available at: https://www.epilepsy.org.au/about-epilepsy/understanding-epilepsy/seizure-types-and-classification/","\u200cGhulaxe Y, Joshi A, Chavada J, Huse S, Kalbande B, Sarda PP. Understanding focal seizures in adults: A comprehensive review. Cureus [Internet]. 2023;15(11):e48173. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10693312/#:~:text=onset%20aware%20seizures-","\u200c"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51404"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16452"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51404"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-28T09:31:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-28T09:31:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9143"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65955"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGr